	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Even if you have el cheapo 10,000-erase flash memory, and you develop 5 days a week, that's still 10 hardware builds a day for four years. But most flash memories are an order of magnitude more durable than 10,000 writes. For instance, AMD's Am29F010 has 100K erases for each of its eight 16 KiB sectors. The best thing about flash vs. SRAM is that flash is more reliable if you want to run on a non-CopyNES, such as if you have your developers using one cart on a CopyNES and your play testers using another cart.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

